snippet.textDisplay: A couple of thoughts on the Helo crash....  Interesting things I have noticed... Comedy Central (and various SM sites) have yanked/deleted the (alleged) "Predictive Programing" video from the net. Included is an excuse for this action, "removed out of respect for the family". Add to that, CC (33) is asking people "NOT to share the video on-line..." INGSOC is now busy 'scrubbing the net'. No doubt in a vain attempt. . .  On topic, from what is reported, Kobe Bryant 'owned' a Sakorsky S-76 (model B reported) which is one the MOST reliable, safest Helos/Helicopters in the sky. UNBELIEVEABLE Safety Record, that is why most Air Ambulances and Executive Heli Companies fly the S-76. . . I have spent most of my life, dealing in the world of aircraft , fixed and rotary wing, but mostly in the world of rotor wing … Now I am NOT suggesting ANYTHING, just a few observations that made me go WTF! I watched the 'Breaking News' and from the start... NOTHING looked correct. From the very small brush/ground fire (not a Kerosene, mental and/or plastic fire). The media close up of the crash site, also looked "strange" and I could go into many details, suffice it to say, my first thought was, 'Where is the aircraft?' (one can go on-line and see many Heli crash sites and compare) I see what looks like the engine cowling, but that is it . Another thought was - did they crash on Take-off (one of the most dangerous parts of the Flight profile) and did the pilot have enough elevation to "Auto-rotate" and if so-there should be much more of the aircraft remaining. In "Aircraft Incident Investigation" - "cause and effect" is one of the Holy Grails. To get the 'result' on the ground, one has to think 'what profile was the A/C in when it went critical'. Think Car Crash... 10 mph and hitting a wall...you get a certain "result"... now think 100mph, hitting a wall and the result one would get. To get the destruction that I saw, I can only suggest/think of two profiles... "Fast and Low" flying within the "Dead Man's Curve"... which is FORBOTTEN with ALL professional pilots. Proper take off procedures, requires one to climb through the "DM curve" as quick as possible. That way in case of an "engine failure" one can use the energy stored in the main rotor system to perform a "safe landing" via "auto-rotation". The other is that the Helo went "catastrophic" in flight, eg: a main blade flying off the mast (a near impossibility-FAA Flight Rules and Maintenance) and fell out of the sky. This would result in a much larger fire (even if its just charred ground) and a debris field, but there would still be an aircraft. SO MANY questions. . .  . NTSB National Transportation Safety Board conducts all investigations. "Fog" is entirely BULLSHIT. The S-76 can fly IFR, and in an IFR environment, NO pilot would descend into fog, or any bad weather, in "uncontrolled air-space", eg; anywhere w/o RADAR. Descending "into weather" is suicidal, unless HIGHLY trained (and experienced) in IFR and with RADAR. An intelligent/trained "rotor head" avoids Wx. 1st rule in Flight Training... "stay the fu$# out of the clouds and/or bad Wx". I can still hear my Flight Instructor's words to this day.... from a 'hundred years ago'. As with so many "incidents" the MSM media only seems to confuse the issue, or just outright lies and obfuscates. I have heard so many contradictory reports/stories, its idiotic . . . Maybe "Kobe's" time was up and his "Faustian Bargen" was due. Maybe not.
